<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Higher Education Academy (WSC053)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the Higher Education Academy (WSC053)</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Summary</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This paper argues that in order to address the issues raised by the Inquiry, it is necessary to look earlier in the academic experience of women in STEM subjects.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Key areas that should be explored further r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">elate to the recruitment of women to STEM subjects and the design of curricula in STEM subjects.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It also recommends that further research should be conducted around the transition of female students to postgraduate study. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ul><h2 style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Introduction</span></h2><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Higher Educatio</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n Academy (HEA) works to enhance learning and teaching in higher education. It focuses on inspiring and supporting effective practice in learning and teaching; recognising, rewarding and accrediting excellence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> teaching, and influencing policy, future th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">inking and change. Through providing subject specific support the HEA has an expertise in addressing contemporary challenges facing higher education. The HEA works closely with senior in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">stitutional managers, academics and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> students</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and commissions research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to advance knowledge, broker change and develop new thinking in relation to learning and teaching.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Through its STEM subject cluster and its thematic work in the areas of student access, retention and success, and employability, the HEA’s work is of parti</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cular relevance to this House of Commons inquiry. Notably this response seeks to address the following questions:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">What should the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 8.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-8.5pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">practice?</span></h2><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The HEA considers that there is a need to look earlier in the academic experience of women in STEM subjects in order to make a significant difference to retention later on in their academic career. A recent HEA study into progression to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">postgraduate research provision found that ‘men are more likely to study disciplines at first</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> degree that have a high rate of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> progression to higher </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">degrees (research degrees in particular)’. The report concluded that this ‘might account for some or all of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the gender differences.’</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As such, the HEA suggests that the inquiry includes t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">wo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> interrelated</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> key areas:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Admissions to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">undergraduate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">STEM subjects – how STEM subjects are marketed by universities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Curriculum design.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is a good body of recent eviden</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ce highlighting the importance of the academic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">experience</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to the retention and success of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> students in higher education. The HEFCE / Paul Hamlyn Foundation funded ‘What works? Student retention and success programme’ found that ‘the exact type of interv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ention or approach is less important than the way it is offered and its intended outcomes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.’ </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It recommended that interventions should be designed using the following principles</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Interventions should be embedded in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">mainstream</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> provision.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Interventions should be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">proactive and developmental</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Interventions should be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">relevant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to students’ current academic interests and future aspirations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Interventions should be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">well timed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and use </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">appropriate media</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Interventions should encourage </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">collaboration</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> with fellow students and academics.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Interventions should be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">monitored</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for reach and quality.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The HEA considers that these generic principles should be used by institutions when considering interventions to support the retention and success of female stu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dents in STEM subjects.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Pre-entry and admission</span></h3><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is clear from the available statistics </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> STEM subjects male students significantly outnumber female undergraduate students. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">At undergraduate level, w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hilst there are a few STEM subjects (Biosciences, anatomy and physiology, and pharmacy and pharmacology) where female undergraduate students outnumber male students, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in four areas in particular (computer sciences, engineering and technology, mathematics, a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nd physics) male students significantly outnumber female students.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The recent analysis that was conducted for the HEA on transition to postgraduate taught and research degrees strongly suggests that in order to tackle gender differences at postgraduate le</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">vel, the sector must first resolve issues relating to the recruitment of women to undergraduate courses.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Key to recruiting students from diverse backgrounds is ensuring that initial information provided by higher education providers to pro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">spective underg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">raduate students appeals to a broad audience. For example, the way a course is explained in the university publicity materials such as brochures and websites – its content, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">examples of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">project</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and problem solving </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">activitie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">make the course interestin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g to certain groups. A wider range in course content could result in a higher uptake of STEM degrees by women.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Curriculum design</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">General considerations &amp; evidence</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The HEFCE / Paul Hamlyn Foundation ‘What Works? Student retention and success programme’ fo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">und that ‘at the heart of successful retention and success is a strong sense of belonging in HE for all students. This is more effectively nurtured </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">through</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> mainstream activities that all student participate in.’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The research found that students considered </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">withdrawing from higher education most often in their first semester or after the Christmas vacation. Based on the evidence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and principles (see above) identified as part of the What Works? programme, the HEA has published a ‘Compendium of effective practic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e in higher education’ presenting case studies that detail how higher education providers have developed effective </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">strategies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to tackle issues relating to student transition.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The HEA’s significant body of research suggests that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">avoiding stereotypes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">celebrating diversity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are important factors in the development of curricula</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> suitable for all students irrespective of their background</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">STEM specific considerations and evidence</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">STEM curricula can be designed to be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> more </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">appealing to women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and lead to inc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reased diversity on enrolment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. This could include</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">offering of a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">iverse range of projects and problem solving. With careful design students</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">develop a sense of be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">longing to a STEM profession. For example,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Coventry University </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">has embedded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Humanitaria</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n Engineering</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">within </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">its engineering</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> curriculum, and students are able to study modules focussing on areas such as poverty reduction and post-disaster rebuild scenarios as part of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">their</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> degree.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In response to a survey of female students on male-domina</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ted programmes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the isolation some female students experienced was identified</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in a very male culture and atmosphere,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the survey highlighted their desire to be more fully integrated into communities of practice.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> This evidence suggests that greater consi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">deration could be given to the integration of women in communities of practice by institutions, departments and faculties.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In Engineering, which has a considerably greater number of male than female students, evidence suggests that it is essential to pay</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> particular attention to ensuring that students from under-represented groups are comfortable in the learning environment created within an engineering department.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">M careers?</span></h2><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Based on the available evidence, the HEA suggests that the government should encourage review of curriculum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> design</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">culture</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in STEM </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to encourage equality and d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">iversity with an emphasis on gender.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The government should review ways to encourage universities to foster a culture of belonging to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> STEM profession for female students</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which would lead to the retention of women in academic STEM careers.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Furthermore, the HEA considers that additional res</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">earch is required to explore the lower transition rate of women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in general </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">into postgraduate taught and research degrees.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Paul Wakeling &amp;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Gillian Hampden-Thompson, Transitions to higher degrees across the UK: an analysis of national, institutional and individual differences (2013), available at: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">http://www.heacademy.ac.uk/assets/documents/research/Transition_to_higher_degree_across_the_UK.pdf</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Liz Thomas, ‘Building student engagement and belonging at a time of change: a summary of findings and recommendations from the What Wor</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">ks? Student retention and success programme’ (2012). Available at</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">h